\par After a night of dream-lit snow
s the air turned clear and still. There was a taut blue quality in the January light, a hardness and confidence. The sound of boots on packed snow, the contrails streaked cleanly in the high sky. Weather was very much the point, although I didn't know it 
at first.
\par I turned into our street and walked past men bent over shovels in their driveways, breathing vapor. A squirrel moved along a limb in a flowing motion, a passage so continuous it seemed to be its own physical law, different from the ones we've lear
ned to trust. When I was halfway down the street I saw Heinrich crouched on a small ledge outside our attic window. He wore his camouflage jacket and cap, an outfit with complex meaning for him, at fourteen, struggling to grow and to escape notice simulta
neously, his secrets known to us all. He looked east through binoculars.
\par I went around back to the kitchen. In the entranceway the washer and dryer were vibrating nicely. I could tell from Babette's voice that the person she was talking to on the phone was 
her father. An impatience mixed with guilt and apprehension. I stood behind her, put my cold hands to her cheeks. A little thing I liked to do. She hung up the phone.
\par "Why is he on the roof?"
\par "Heinrich? Something about the train yards," she said. "It was on the radio."
\par "Shouldn't I get him down?"
\par "Why?"
\par "He could fall."
\par "Don't tell him that."
\par "Why not?"
\par "He thinks you underestimate him."
\par "He's on a ledge," I said. 'There must be something I should be doing."
\par 'The more you show concern, the closer he'll go to the edge."
\par "I know that but I still have to get him down."
\par "Coax him back in," she said. "Be sensitive and caring. Get him to talk about himself. Don't make sudden movements."
\par When I got to the attic he was already back inside, standing by the open windo
w, still looking through the glasses. Abandoned possessions were everywhere, oppressive and soul-worrying, creating a weather of their own among the exposed beams and posts, the fiberglass insulation pads.
\par "What happened?"
\par 'The radio said a tank car derailed. But I don't think it derailed from what I could see. I think it got rammed and something punched a hole in it. There's a lot of smoke and I don't like the looks of it."
\par "What does it look like?"
\par He handed me the binoculars and stepped aside. Without cl
imbing onto the ledge I couldn't see the switching yard and the car or cars in question. But the smoke was plainly visible, a heavy black mass hanging in the air beyond the river, more or less shapeless.
\par "Did you see fire engines?"
\par "They're all over the place," he said. "But it looks to me like they're not getting too close. It must be pretty toxic or pretty explosive stuff, or both."
\par "It won't come this way."
\par "How do you know?"
\par "It just won't. The point is you shouldn't be standing on icy ledges. It worries Baba."
\par "You think if you tell me it worries her, I'll feel guilty and not do it. But if you tell me it worries you, I'll do it all the time."
\par "Shut the window," I told him.
\par We went down to the kitchen. Steffie was looking through the brightly colored mail for coupons, lotteries and contests. This was}{\f111\fs16\insrsid2510831\charrsid15561226  }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 
the last day of the holiday break for the grade school and high school. Classes on the Hill would resume in a week. I sent Heinrich outside to clear snow from the walk. I watched him stand out there, utterly 
still, his head turned slightly, a honed awareness in his stance. It took me a while to realize he was listening to the sirens beyond the river.
\par An hour later he was back in the attic, this time with a radio and highway map. I climbed the narrow stairs, borrowed the glasses and looked again. It was still there, a slightly larger accumulation, a towering mass in fact, maybe a little blacker now.

\par "The radio calls it a feathery plume," he said. "But it's not a plume."
\par "What is it?"
\par "Like a shapeless growing thing. A dark black breathing thing of smoke. Why do they call it a plume?"
\par "Air time is valuable. They can't go into long tortured descriptions. Have they said what kind of chemical it is?"
\par "It's called Nyodene Derivative or Nyodene D. It was in a movie we saw in school on toxic wastes. These videotaped rats."
\par "What does it cause?"
\par 'The movie wasn't sure what it does to humans. Mainly it was rats growing urgent lumps."
\par "That's what the movie said. What does the radio say?"
\par "At first they said skin irritation and sweaty palms. But now they say nausea, vomiting, shortness of breath."
\par "This is human nausea we're talking about. Not rats."
\par "Not rats," he said.
\par I gave him the binoculars.
\par "Well it won't come this way."
\par "How do you know?" he said.
\par "I just know. It's perfectly calm and still today. And when there's a wind at this time of year, it blows that way, not this way."
\par "What if it blows this way?"
\par "It won't."
\par "Just this one time."
\par "It won't. Why should it?"
\par He paused a beat and said in a flat tone, 'They just closed part of the interstate."
\par 'They would want to do that, of course."
\par "Why?"
\par 'They just would. A sensible precaution. A way to facilitate movement of service vehicles and such. Any number of reasons that have nothing to do with wind or wind direction."
\par Babette's head appeared at the top of the stairway. She said a neighbor had told her the spill from the tank car was thirty-five thousand gallons. People were being told to stay out of the area. A feathe
ry plume hung over the site. She also said the girls were complaining of sweaty palms.
\par 'There's been a correction," Heinrich told her. 'Tell them they ought to be throwing up."
\par A helicopter flew over, headed in the direction of the accident. The voice on the radio said: "Available for a limited time only with optional megabyte hard disk."
\par Babette's head sank out of sight. I watched Heinrich tape the road map to two posts. Then I went down to the kitchen to pay some bills, aware of colored spots whirling atomically somewhere to the right and behind me.
\par Steffie said, "Can you see the feathery plume from the attic window?"
\par "It's not a plume."
\par "But will we have to leave our homes?"
\par "Of course not."
\par "How do you know?"
\par "I just know."
\par "Remember how we couldn't go to school?"
\par 'That was inside. This is outside."
\par We heard police sirens blowing. I watched Steffie's lips form the sequence: }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 wow wow wow wow. }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 
She smiled in a certain way when she saw me watching, as though gently startled out of some absent-minded pleasure.
\par Denise walked in, rubbing her hands on her jeans.
\par "They're using snow-blowers to blow stuff onto the spill," she said.
\par "What kind of stuff?"
\par "I don't know but it's supposed to make the spill harmless, which doesn't explain what they're doing about the actual plume."
\par "They're keeping it from getting bigger," I said. "When do we eat?"
\par "I don't know but if it gets any bigger it'll get here with or without a wind."
\par "It won't get here," I said.
\par "How do you know?"
\par "Because it won't."
\par She looked at her palms and went upstairs. The phone rang. Babette walked into the kitchen and picked it up. She looked at me as she listened. I wrote two checks, periodically glancing up to see if she was still looking at me. She seemed to study my face 
for the hidden meaning of the message she was receiving. I puckered my lips in a way I knew she disliked.
\par 'That was the Stovers," she said. "They spoke directly with the weather center outside Glassboro. They're not calling it a feathery plume anymore."
\par "What are they calling it?"
\par "A black billowing cloud."
\par "That's a little more accurate, which means they're coming to grips with the thing. Good."
\par "There's more," she said. "It's expected that some sort of air mass may be moving down from Canada."
\par "There's always an air mass moving down from Canada."
\par 'That's true," she said. 'There's certainly nothing new in that. And since Canada is to the north, if the billowing cloud is blown due south, it will miss us by a comfortable margin."
\par "When do we eat?" I said.
\par We heard sirens again, a different set this time, a larger sound\emdash  not police, fire, ambulance. They were air-raid sirens, I realized, and they seemed to be blowing in Sawyersville, a small community to the northeast.
\par Steffie washed her hands at the kitchen sink and went upstairs. Babette started taking things out of the refrigerator. I grabbed her by the inside of the thigh as she passed the table. She squirmed deliciously, a package of frozen corn in her hand.
\par "Maybe we ought to be more concerned about the billowing cloud," she said. "It's because of the kids we keep saying nothing's going to happen. We don't want to scare them."
\par "Nothing }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 is }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 going to happen."
\par "I know nothing's going to happen, you know nothing's going to happen. But at some level we ought to think about it anyway, just in case."
\par "These things happen to poor people who live in exposed areas. Society is set up in such a way that it's the poor and the uneducated who suffer the main impact of natural and man-made disasters. People in low-lying areas
 get the floods, people in shanties get the hurricanes and tornados. I'm a college professor. Did you ever see a college professor rowing a boat down his own street in one of those TV floods? We live in a neat and pleasant town near a college with a quain
t name. These things don't happen in places like Blacksmith."
\par She was sitting on my lap by now. The checks, bills, contest forms and coupons were scattered across the table.
\par "Why do you want dinner so early?" she said in a sexy whisper.
\par "I missed lunch."
\par "Shall I do some chili-fried chicken?"
\par "First-rate."
\par "Where is Wilder?" she said, thick-voiced, as I ran my hands over her breasts, trying with my teeth to undo her bra clip through the blouse.
\par "I don't know. Maybe Murray stole him."
\par "I ironed your gown," she said.
\par "Great, great."
\par "Did you pay the phone bill?"
\par "Can't find it."
\par We were both thick-voiced now. Her arms were crossed over my arms in such a way that I could read the serving suggestions}{\f111\fs16\insrsid2510831\charrsid15561226  }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 
on the box of corn niblets in her left hand.
\par "Let's think about the billowing cloud. Just a little bit, okay? It could be dangerous."
\par "Everything in tank cars is dangerous. But the effects are mainly long-range and all we have to do is stay out of the way."
\par "Let's just be sure to keep it in the back of our mind," she said, getting up to smash an ice tray repeatedly on the rim of the sink, dislodging the cubes in groups of two and three.
\par I puckered my lips at her. Then I climbed to the attic one more time. Wilder was up there with Heinrich, whose fast glance in my direction contained a certain practiced accusation.
\par "They're not calling it the feathery plume anymore," he said, not meeting my eyes, as if to spare himself the pain of my embarrassment.
\par "I already knew that."
\par 'They're calling it the black billowing cloud." "Good."
\par "Why is that good?"
\par "It means they're looking the thing more or less squarely in the eye. They're on top of the situation."
