nt to know. There are only three or four places she could have gone to get the prescription filled, within a reasonable distance. A pharmacist can tell us what the stuff is for. I'll get in the car first thing in the morning."
\par "I already did that," she said.
\par "When?"
\par "Around Christmas. I went to three drugstores and talked to the Indians behind the counters in the back."
\par "I think they're Pakistanis."
\par "Whatever."
\par "What did they tell you about Dylar?"
\par "Never heard of it."
\par "Did you ask them to look it up? They must have lists of the most recent medications. Supplements, updates."
\par "They looked. It's not on any list."
\par "Unlisted," I said.
\par "We'll have to call her doctor."
\par "I'll call him now. I'll call him at home."
\par "Surprise him," she said, with a certain ruthlessness.
\par "If I get him at home, he won't be screened by an answering service, a receptionist, a nurse, the young and good-humored doctor who shares his suite of offices and whose role in life is to treat the established doctor's rejects. Once you're shunted fro
