\par "You would call a doctor at home to talk about memory lapse. If everyone with memory lapse called a doctor at home, what would we have? The ripple effect would be tremendous."
\par I told him the lapses were frequent.
\par "Frequent. I know your wife. This is the wi
fe who came to me one night with a crying child. 'My child is crying.' She would come to a medical doctor who is a private corporation and ask him to treat a child for crying. Now I pick up the phone and it's the husband. You would call a doctor in his ho
me after ten o'clock at night. You would say to him, 'Memory lapse.' Why not tell me she has gas? Call me at home for gas?"
\par "Frequent and prolonged, doctor. It has to be the medication."
\par "What medication?"
\par "Dylar."
\par "Never heard of it."
\par "A small white tablet. Comes in an amber bottle."
\par "You would describe a tablet as small and white and expect a doctor to respond, at home, after ten at night. Why not tell me it is round? This is crucial to our case."
\par "It's an unlisted drug."
\par "I never saw it. I certainly never prescribed it for your wife. She's a very healthy woman so far as it's within my ability to ascertain such things, being subject as I am to the same human failings as the next fellow."
\par This sounded like a malpractice disclaimer. Maybe he was reading it fr
om a printed card like a detective informing a suspect of his constitutional rights. I thanked him, hung up, called my own doctor at home. He answered on the seventh ring, said he thought Dylar was an island in the Persian Gulf, one of those oil terminals
