\par In Don DeLillo's first novel, }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 Americana, }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 published in 1971, a t
elevision producer embarked on a cross-country trip, camera in hand, from Madison Avenue to Dealey Plaza. His desire to nail down the gas-driven, motel-housed American soul indicated the scope of DeLillo's ambition and established one of his abiding theme
s
: Americans' fondness for their own reflection. In seven subsequent novels he's watched us watch ourselves, measuring in keenly observant prose the depth and cost of that self-absorption. His richest conceit in developing this vision has been technology's
 ability to project the reassuring likeness\emdash hence television's status as a character in many books. But broadcast waves just mediate the fascination; the mirror game is a human one. Its motivation is expressed without embarrassment by }{
\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 Americano's }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 narrator: 
"When I began to wonder who I was, I took the simple step of lathering my face and shaving. It all became so clear, so wonderful. I was blue-eyed David Bell. Obviously my life depended on this fact."
\par Working a territory thick with social critics, DeLillo spares us the polemics. In the current New }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 Criterion, }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 
he's accused of passing cynical judgments, but criticism of that sort misinterprets his tone. His tack is inquisitive, almost anthropological, as he serves up a variety of American specialties like college football }{
\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 (End Zone), }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 leftists and the CIA }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 (Running Dog), }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 rock music }{
\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 (Great Jones Street), }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 and Wall Street }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 (Players). }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 
An intensely visual writer, DeLillo can locate and dissect the telling freeze\emdash porchfront cocktails on a suburban Sunday or downtown Manhattan's rush-hour ballet. He illuminates the idiosyncrasies of our}{\f111\fs16\insrsid2510831\charrsid15561226  
