The passage describes air travel, one of that novel's symbols of American-made alienation: "We take no sense impressions with us, no voices, none of the windy blast of aircraft on the tarmac, or the white noise of flight, or the hours waiting" }{
\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 (The Names, }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 7). Like }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 The Names, White Noise }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 
is narrated by a middle-aged father who seeks refuge from the largeness of things\emdash the complexities of information and communication that surround him\emdash in his marriage and children. He finds in family life "the one medium of s
ense knowledge in which an astonishment of heart is routinely contained" (117), and then, when family is lost to him as a source of safety, succumbs to a visceral obsession with violence; this obsession propels the second halves of the two novels' plots. 
The fear of death, which infects Owen Brademas and the cult in }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 The Names, }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 moves to the center of }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 White Noise, }{
