\par In "Waves and Radiation," the first of the three parts of }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 White Noise, }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 DeLillo represents with acute specificity the quotidian life of the Glad-ney family
\emdash Jack and Babette and their four children from various earlier marriages. Though tinged with some satire and foreboding, Part I establishes "around-the-house" expectations, the "good company" of }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 
White Noise. }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 As in }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 End Zone, }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 
which has a parallel structure of two balancing sets of chapters surrounding a center of irrational activity, "good company" abruptly shifts in Part II, "The Airborne Toxic Event." }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 White Noise }{
\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 becomes a disaster novel. While the Gladneys' safety is suddenly destroyed by the chemical spill that forces them to evacuate their home and town, the reader's expectations of the marital changes and va
cations recorded in "around-the-house" realism are deconfirmed. In "The Airborne Toxic Event," DeLillo describes the chemical cloud, the process of evacuation, and several non-Gladney evacuees, but he also quickly subverts the conventions of disaster fict
ion. The cast of thousands and the long-running suspense of this subgenre are radically contracted in }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 White Noise. }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 
In DeLillo's disaster, no one dies. The timing of the disaster within the novel is also skewed: preceded by twenty chapters, the 54 pages of P
art II are followed by nineteen chapters as DeLillo quickly shifts from the event to his characters' response. Glad-ney, his family, and the town of Blacksmith look just as they did before this new kind of technological disaster, because its effects are i
nvisible to the naked eye. Their response is to information\emdash quantified measures of exposure, possible long-range consequences\emdash 
rather than to entities, the scattered corpses or destroyed buildings of conventional disaster fiction. The disaster of }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 White Noise }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 
is, ultimately, the new knowledge that seeps into the future from the imploded toxic event.
\par In Part III, "Dylarama," the reader understands that DeLillo is not only successively reversing two subgenres but is also, in the whole of }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 White Noise, }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 
inverting yet another subgenre\emdash the college novel\emdash 
to illustrate for whom new knowledge is a threat. The book opens with Professor Jack Gladney, head of the Hitler Studies Department at College-on-the-Hill, describing the return of students in the autumn. It closes wit
h summer recess an academic year later. Several of Glad-ney's colleagues have roles, and there is one classroom scene; but the political intrigues and intellectual adventures one expects from the college novel occur primarily within the confines of Gladne
y's home. His very contemporary family is wired to more sources of information than was a college student of Gladney's generation. While the university in }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 White Noise }{
\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 is presented as trivialized by the nostalgic study of popular and youth culture, Gladney's
 children are making his family a center of learning. The irony of this inverted situation is that the professor and his teacher-wife attempt to resist knowledge and regress into nostalgia while their children, despite their fears, move forward and outwar
d into the Age of Information, into awareness of large, complexly related systems. For the parents, this attitude toward knowledge is madness\emdash 
as, for some readers, is DeLillo's inversion of the college novel, his making the Gladney children fearful prodigies. However, both the rapid shifts and reversals exist within a general verisimilitude, the grounding for DeLillo's mockery and exaggeration.

\par Although generically and rhetorically doubled, }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 White Noise, }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 when compared with }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 The Names }{
\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 or even with }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 Americana, }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 is
 structurally and stylistically simple; it lacks their spatial forms, temporal dislocations, framed analogies, overlapping subtexts, and multiple voices. The physical action of }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 White Noise }{
\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 is constricted and repetitive: Jack Gladney evades literal death by
 leaving Blacksmith and traveling to nearby Iron City in the novel's first half, and in the second half he returns to Iron City in quest of a drug that would let him evade his fear of death. Much of the intellectual action\emdash 
Gladney's dialogues and meditations\emdash is equally looping and reductive, marked by circular logic and sophistical argument. Like David Bell of }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 Americana, }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 
who does not recognize that the auto test track at the end of the novel is a symbolic repetition of his job at the beginning, Gladney ends in Blacksmith where he began\emdash 
with the reader unsure of how much the professor has learned from his spatial loops and compulsive repetitions. Other characters offer little assistance to the reader who attempts to gauge Gladney's development. Although }{
\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 White Noise }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 displays some of the doubling also seen in }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 The Names }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 and 
}{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 Americana, }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 the characters in Gladney's family, his acquaintances, and his friends exist primarily as sources of information or stimuli for Gladney, not 
as persons with plots and complex lives of their own.
\par DeLillo packs the text with disparate cultural signs and symptoms, but the simple chronological continuity with which Gladney orders his narrative has the effect of reducing it to a collection with appa
rently minimal connections, more an aggregate than a system. Although Gladney tells his tale primarily in the past tense, he seems to be recording both the trivia and trauma as they happen, not\emdash like David Bell and James Axton\emdash 
forming the materials from a l
ater perspective. Gladney seldom recalls the past before the novel's events begin, and he plans the future only when forced to. "May the days be aimless. Let the seasons drift. Do not advance the action according to a plan" (98) \emdash 
 these are his desires before the disaster. Gladney allows gaps between episodes, sometime suddenly shifts from description to dialogue or meditation, and composes in short chapters. Gary Harkness of }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 
End Zone }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 used the same methods to create discontinuity within a basic chronological order. The only technique to intrude upon the novel's}{\f111\fs16\insrsid2510831\charrsid15561226  }{
\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 illusion of natural or unsophisticated recall is DeLillo's insertion of lists. Always composed of three items, usually the names of products, the lists do not always seem to be in Gladney's consciousn
ess; rather, they are part of the circumambient noise in which he exists, a reminder of the author's presence, his knowledge of a larger context of communications. The lists are also a small analogue of the reductive organization of the text as a whole.

\par Gladney's sentences are like these lists: short, noun dominated, sometimes fragmentary, with few of the convolutions or Jamesian subordinations that show up in }{\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 The Names. }{
\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 Often lexically and syntactically repetitious, Gladney's strings of declarations effect
 a primer style, an expression not of ignorance (for Gladney knows the language of the humanities) but of something like shock, a seeming inability to sort into contexts and hierarchies the information he receives and the thinking he does. Gladney's accou
nt of his life resembles the narration of a near-disaster that he hears at the Iron City airport, where a man "wearily" and "full of a gentle resignation" (90) describes the terror of preparing for a crash landing. When not neutrally\emdash 
almost distractedly\emdash  re
cording, Gladney's voice does rise to complaint and, more frequently, to series of rhetorical questions for which he has few answers. A character who has to be forced to think and who resists the process, the self-limiting narrator of }{
\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 White Noise }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 resembles Gary Harkness, who is as frozen by guilt as Gladney is by fear. But where the blank-faced narration of }{
\i\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 End Zone }{\f111\fs16\insrsid10622856\charrsid15561226 occasionally hinted that Harkness was playing a game, was intentionally unreliable, the survivor style of Gladney suggests a shrunken reliabili
ty. The reader perceives evasion, rather than power.
